: formula_14

===Other calculations===
For a given mass formula_15 (in grams) of an isotope with atomic mass formula_16 (in g/mol) and a half-life of formula_17 (in s), the radioactivity can be calculated using:

:formula_18

With formula_19 = , the Avogadro constant.

Since formula_20 is the number of moles (formula_21), the amount of radioactivity formula_22 can be calculated by:

:formula_23

For instance, on average each gram of potassium contains 117 micrograms of 40K (all other naturally occurring isotopes are stable) that has a formula_17 of = , and has an atomic mass of 39.964 g/mol, so the amount of radioactivity associated with a gram of potassium is 30 Bq.

==Examples==
==Applications==
The specific activity of radionuclides is particularly relevant when it comes to select them for production for therapeutic pharmaceuticals, as well as for immunoassays or other diagnostic procedures, or assessing radioactivity in certain environments, among several other biomedical applications.

